HEADWORD: Epicure
<hw>Ep"i*cure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Epicurus</ets>, Gr. <?/, a famous Greek philosopher, who has been
regarded, but erroneously, as teaching a doctrine of refined
voluptuousness.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A follower of Epicurus; an
Epicurean.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One devoted to dainty or luxurious sensual
enjoyments, esp. to the luxuries of the table.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Voluptuary; sensualist.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Epicurean</ent>⟦br⟧
